id, accessible reexamination of the role of nuclear weapons and their prominence in U.S. security strategy. Nichols explains why strategies built for the Cold War have survived into the twenty-first century, and he illustrates how America's nearly unshakable belief in the utility of nuclear arms has hindered U.S. and international attempts to slow the nuclear programs of volatile regimes in North Korea and Iran. From a solid historical foundation, Nichols makes the compelling argument that to end the danger of worldwide nuclear holocaust, the United States must take the lead in abandoning unrealistic threats of nuclear force and then create a new and more stable approach to deterrence for the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNational securityzUnited States. 0aNuclear disarmamentzUnited States. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aSecurity, International. 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220906840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209068423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209068.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041352-6  Penn Press eBook Package Law & Political Science  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  a